metadata.name: Mythic Latent Glitches  #205
metadata.description:
What is even real and what is artificial?

In the contemporary light, the division between real and artificial loses weight as the concepts become more and more intertwined. In this work, the artist combines the human and generative inputs, in a counterintuitive manner, by allowing AI to design the organic elements and using the human hand to incorporate artificial glitches. What seemingly emerges as natural forms, was imagined solely by GAN, seeing the world through the limited examples through the photographer’s lenses. Artist’s role is also reversed, as their goal is to design the visual destruction process of the organic forms. Glitch is a malfunction of perception, it symbolizes the confusion caused by not being able to comprehend. 

The human fascination with metaphysical forces spans many centuries. While Pagan mythology created gods living in deep forests and under-explored territories, nowadays we approach technology with somewhat similar awe, fascination, and fear. 

The project has been developed in multiple stages. It started with an inspiration by the Lithuanian landscape and research of the ancient myths and legends. The photography aimed at capturing the mysterious, spanning months and years of different experiences. A custom pre-trained artist’s GAN model was then trained on a collection of several hundred photographs in high resolution. Selected outputs were curated by artist and included as a starting canvas for the next stage. Then, a set of stochastic manipulations were programmed to create alternative narratives through the visual destruction. Fog turns into smoke into burning radioactive forest in an unpredictable manner, guided by the random variables, their boundaries crafted by artist.  

Read more on the project website:
ivonatau.com/mythic-latent-glitches

- Use the "A" key to animate (if "Animated" feature is present).
- Press any key to stop the animation.
- Use the "S" key to export an image.

metadata.name: (Anti)thesis #62
metadata.description:
This is my first fxhash work. It is a generative, deterministic, object-oriented algorithm written entirely in p5.js. With the exception of two very rare background colours, the colour palettes are not pre-selected but entirely generated using your transaction hash.

The algorithm plays on the concept of Antithesis (/ænˈtɪθəsɪs/ - direct contrast; opposition) by using opposing forces to generate tension (and occasional calm) between forms on the page and the spaces in between. Inspiration was also drawn from works and advice from the great Daniel Catt (@revdancatt).

I hope you like it. Thanks for your support.
tallzy

metadata.name: MAGNETIK #192
metadata.description:
The output of MAGNETIK reminds me of what tornadoes do to our cities and buildings, yet I imagine the pieces that are about to break off and fly away to be made of metal foil and they do so because of a magnetic force that is pulling them away from where they belong…  This one is also a charity run :  
- 20% of the primary sales will go directly to the Processing Foundation, 

- Remaining 80% will be donated to a group of individuals that raise money to buy computers for less fortunate architecture students in a university in the eastern part of Turkey. Please read the next paragraph for a detailed explanation

- I will decide what to do with the secondary sales later if there will be any.

About the majority (80%) of the donation : I decided that the donations should be done in a double-blind way, the donator does not know who they are donating to, and the receivers of the donation will not know from whom the donation is coming from, hence I will transfer the funds these individuals mentioned to act as a middle-step. I feel like this is a hard thing to provide a solid proof for, so I recommend if you have doubts and/or straight away do not trust me or this process, do not mint. I will only be able to provide proof of transfer of funds to a third-party. I trust the people I am sending the funds to, we have done this before (not to brag or anything) and I know that we are affecting younger people’s life in a good way. Also, I believe that the funds raised from this project alone will not be enough to buy one decent config. computer by itself, if it were so, I would have done it differently.  About MAGNETIK :  
MAGNETIK plays on the idea of distorting and breaking grids by employing an illusion of fake 3D and tries to make the resulting composition look good with rhythm and color harmony.
 
- 21 palettes,
- 2 background modes : lights on / lights off,
- 3 grid types,
- plus some surprise features…

I encourage you to try and see the variations before minting :)  2 of the grid types are based on https://gorillasun.de/blog/an-algorithm-for-irregular-grids by Ahmad Moussa ( https://twitter.com/gorillasu ) and used with his knowledge and kind permission.

gradient formulas are based on https://twitter.com/takawo/status/1505876107492720651?s=20&t=S9aU_oNYyjBieBcEmvUV-g
by Takawo Shunsuke ( https://twitter.com/takawo ) and used with his knowledge and kind permission.

Thank you all in advance and have a good day!

DISCLAIMER : I am not a good coder, I have tried to fix my past mistakes from my earlier projects to make some room for new mistakes :) I am hoping that there isn’t any huge bugs or anything left so you can enjoy your mint! Please hit me up if you have any concerns after minting and we can discuss a solution.

metadata.name: Sunset in Paradise #66
metadata.description:
Hundreds of Walkers descend the screen drawing a sky, sea and the sun reflection; creating a twilight scene of a sunset or possibly a sunrise depending on which coast your paradise can be found. 
Features - 32 Palettes 
5 Possible background colors per palette
3 different complexities of sky:
	-Refined - 3 colors (25% chance)
	-Complex - 5 colors (25% chance)
	-Normal - 4 colors (50% chance)
2 possible border colors: 
	Matching the sun color (40% chance) 
	Matching the sea color (60% chance)
2 different stroke thickness: 
	Fine (25% chance) 
	Medium-point (75% chance) 
Different amounts of Walkers for Sky, Sea and reflection.

Made by @p1x3lboy in p5.js
June 2022

metadata.name: Urban Flora #456
metadata.description:
Urban Flora is a generative artwork exploring interplay of natural and artificial forms created by Marcin Ignac / @marcinignac

http://marcinignac.com/projects/urban-flora/

The project was inspired by the 3/4/5G network infrastructure more and more present in the parks and greenery of our cities. Final Urban Flora transformed into a study of abandoned structures of a long forgotten civilisation.

The whole image is generative and/or procedural. Leaves are parametric, twigs and trees use the space colonisation algorithm, and the geometry is based on platonic solids transformed though series of operations.

Features determined at the time of minting:
- one of the platonic solids or a prism
- one of 15 geometry transformations
- a color theme
- leaves or detailed twigs
- leaf's spread and the amount of ridges

'g' / 'tree finger tap' - resolution and export
'drag' - rotate
'scroll' - zoom (on desktop)

Please note the project needs a decent GPU.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--
With dedication to my wife.
